  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "At MRL 5, SQA requires full configuration management, automated regression testing, and independent code review. The CFD solver (OpenFOAM 9) has documented version control and unit tests, but independent third-party code review has not been completed and regression test coverage for hemolysis-specific routines is 61%, below the 80% threshold required at this risk level.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/sqa-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "SQA achievedLevel >= 4 requires: (1) full configuration management with tagged releases, (2) automated regression suite covering >=80% of hemolysis-relevant code paths, (3) independent third-party code review documented and resolved, and (4) traceability from requirements to test cases. All four criteria must be satisfied."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Code verification was performed using manufactured solutions for the Navier-Stokes solver, confirming second-order spatial convergence. However, the power-law hemolysis transport equation has only been verified against analytical solutions for simplified 1D cases; full 3D manufactured solution verification for the hemolysis scalar transport is absent, leaving a gap at the required Gradation 4 level.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/code-verification-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Numerical code verification at Gradation 4 requires: manufactured solution verification for all governing equations including hemolysis scalar transport in 3D rotating frame, documented order-of-accuracy confirmation, and verification of boundary condition implementations. Partial verification of flow solver alone is insufficient."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted (4.2M, 12.1M, and 31.4M cells). Richardson extrapolation yields a discretization error estimate of 8.3% for the NIH quantity of interest. At MRL 5, the required level demands discretization error below 5% with formal GCI documentation. The achieved error exceeds this threshold and the fine-grid solution has not yet converged to within the required tolerance.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/discretization-error-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Discretization error at Gradation 4 requires: formal Grid Convergence Index (GCI) analysis per Celik et al. 2008, NIH discretization error < 5% on the fine grid, apparent order of convergence within 10% of formal order, and monotonic convergence demonstrated across all three refinement levels."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "rationale": "The FDA benchmark experimental dataset provides detailed documentation of test conditions including fluid temperature (37 ± 0.5 °C), hematocrit (35 ± 2%), blood analog composition, inlet flow waveform, and pump rotational speed measured via optical encoder (±5 RPM). All five operating points used in validation are within the documented test envelope. Experimental uncertainty is quantified via repeat measurements (n=5 per condition) and reported as 95% confidence intervals.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/test-conditions-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Test conditions at Gradation 4 requires: full documentation of all controlled parameters with measurement uncertainty, traceability to calibrated instruments, at least 5 repeat measurements per operating point, and confirmation that test conditions match COU operating envelope bounds within stated tolerances."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Output comparison is the most critical shortfall. The primary QoI (NIH) shows relative errors of 55% and 76% at the two principal operating points, far exceeding the 20% acceptance threshold. Comparison metrics include relative error, validation uncertainty (Uval), and agreement factor (E/Uval). At all five operating conditions, E/Uval > 1.0, indicating that the model-experiment discrepancy cannot be explained by combined experimental and numerical uncertainty alone. Systematic over-prediction is consistent across conditions, suggesting a model form error in the hemolysis constitutive law.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/output-comparison-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Output comparison at Gradation 4 requires: relative error in primary QoI < 20% at all validation points, E/Uval <= 1.0 at >= 80% of operating conditions, systematic bias < 10% across the operating range, and quantified comparison using both point estimates and uncertainty intervals."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "The primary QoI (Normalized Index of Hemolysis, NIH) is directly clinically relevant and maps to the regulatory acceptance criterion (NIH < 0.1 g/100L). Secondary QoIs (pressure head, wall shear stress distributions) are also tracked and support interpretation of hemolysis predictions. The QoI definition is consistent between the computational model output and the experimental measurement protocol.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/qoi-relevance-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "QoI relevance at Gradation 3 requires: primary QoI directly linked to regulatory decision criterion, consistent QoI definition between simulation and experiment, and documented mapping from model output to clinical endpoint."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Validation was conducted on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which is representative but not identical to the target VAD device. The impeller diameter differs by 12% and the volute geometry is simplified. Operating conditions in validation overlap with 4 of 5 COU operating points. The use of a surrogate geometry introduces extrapolation uncertainty not fully captured in the UQ analysis, preventing achievement of Gradation 4.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/validation-relevance-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Validation activity relevance at Gradation 4 requires: validation performed on device geometry within 5% geometric similarity to COU device, all COU operating points covered by validation conditions, and documented assessment of extrapolation uncertainty when surrogate geometries are used."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence was monitored via residual norms for all transport equations. All simulations achieved residual reduction of at least 5 orders of magnitude. The hemolysis scalar transport equation converged to L-infinity residual < 1e-8. Round-off error is negligible given double-precision arithmetic. Solver error is estimated at < 0.1% of the NIH prediction and is not a limiting factor in the overall credibility assessment.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/solver-error-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Numerical solver error at Gradation 3 requires: documented iterative convergence with residual reduction >= 5 orders of magnitude, demonstration that solver error is < 1% of the primary QoI, and use of double-precision arithmetic throughout."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Simulation setup was performed by two independent analysts following a documented simulation protocol. Boundary condition inputs were cross-checked against experimental records. Mesh generation was reviewed by a senior engineer not involved in the primary analysis. No use errors were identified during the independent review. The simulation protocol is version-controlled and traceable.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/use-error-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Use error at Gradation 3 requires: independent review of simulation setup by a qualified engineer, documented simulation protocol with version control, cross-check of boundary conditions against experimental records, and no unresolved discrepancies identified in the review."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "The hemolysis model employs the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law constitutive relation, which was developed from Couette viscometer data under simplified shear conditions. Application to complex three-dimensional turbulent flows in rotating impeller passages introduces significant model form uncertainty. The k-omega SST turbulence model has known limitations in predicting turbulent stresses in regions of high streamline curvature near the impeller blade leading edges. Sensitivity analysis demonstrates that NIH predictions vary by a factor of 2.8 across plausible turbulence model choices (k-epsilon, k-omega SST, RSM), indicating that the model form choice is a dominant source of prediction error and has not been resolved at the required level.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/model-form-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Model form at Gradation 4 requires: systematic evaluation of model form uncertainty via multiple turbulence model comparisons with experimental data, hemolysis constitutive law validated in flow regimes representative of rotating impeller conditions, and model form uncertainty contribution to total prediction uncertainty < 30%."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Key model inputs include blood rheological properties (viscosity, density), hemolysis power-law coefficients (C, alpha, beta), and inlet velocity profiles. Rheological properties are well-characterized from literature with documented uncertainty. However, the power-law coefficients C=3.62e-5, alpha=2.416, and beta=0.785 are derived from a single historical dataset and their uncertainty has not been formally quantified through a systematic parameter identification study. Monte Carlo propagation uses assumed coefficient uncertainty ranges that lack experimental grounding, preventing achievement of Gradation 4.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/model-inputs-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Model inputs at Gradation 4 requires: all primary model inputs characterized with formally quantified uncertainty from experimental data, hemolysis power-law coefficients identified via systematic parameter estimation with confidence intervals, and sensitivity analysis demonstrating which inputs contribute most to output uncertainty."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "The FDA benchmark dataset provides measurements at 5 operating conditions with 5 repeat measurements each (n=25 total hemolysis measurements). Blood analog fluid (porcine blood, hematocrit 35%) is consistent with the COU specification. Sample preparation protocol is documented and traceable. Inter-sample variability is within accepted limits (CV < 15% per condition). The test sample set is adequate for the validation scope.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/test-samples-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Test samples at Gradation 3 requires: minimum 5 repeat measurements per operating condition, documented sample preparation protocol, fluid properties consistent with COU specification, and inter-sample coefficient of variation < 20%."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Computational boundary conditions (inlet flow rate, rotational speed, outlet pressure) were set to match experimental conditions within documented measurement uncertainty. Fluid properties in the simulation (density 1050 kg/m3, viscosity 3.5 mPa·s) correspond to the experimentally measured porcine blood properties. Temperature boundary conditions match the experimental 37°C setpoint. Equivalency is documented in the simulation setup report with direct comparison to experimental records.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/input-equivalency-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Input parameter equivalency at Gradation 3 requires: documented mapping between all experimental control parameters and corresponding simulation boundary conditions, fluid property equivalency confirmed within 5% for all primary properties, and any deviations from exact equivalency assessed for their impact on QoI predictions."
      }
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/vad-hemolysis-not-accepted",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-board",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Not accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for CFD hemolysis prediction of the VAD device at MRL 5 is NOT ACCEPTED based on documented shortfalls in four credibility factors relative to required levels. The most critical deficiencies are: (1) Output comparison (achieved Gradation 2 vs. required Gradation 4): NIH predictions exceed experimental measurements by 55–76% across primary operating conditions, with E/Uval > 1.0 at all five validation points, indicating model-experiment discrepancy exceeds combined uncertainty; (2) Model form (achieved Gradation 2 vs. required Gradation 4): the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model exhibits a factor of 2.8 variation in NIH predictions across plausible turbulence model choices, and the k-omega SST model is not validated for high-curvature rotating impeller flows; (3) Software quality assurance (achieved Gradation 3 vs. required Gradation 4): independent third-party code review is absent and regression test coverage is below the required threshold; (4) Numerical code verification (achieved Gradation 3 vs. required Gradation 4): manufactured solution verification has not been completed for the hemolysis scalar transport equation in 3D rotating reference frames. Additional shortfalls in discretization error (8.3% vs. 5% threshold), model inputs (unquantified power-law coefficient uncertainty), and validation activity relevance (surrogate geometry extrapolation) further undermine confidence. The systematic over-prediction of hemolysis, combined with unresolved model form uncertainty, means the model cannot reliably demonstrate that VAD hemolysis remains below the clinical safety threshold. Acceptance of this model for regulatory decision-making would introduce unacceptable risk of under-estimating patient hemolysis exposure. Remediation requires: resolved turbulence model selection with experimental validation in rotating flow regimes, formal parameter identification for hemolysis model coefficients, completion of 3D code verification, and independent SQA review.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
